For ZYG we always have $\alpha > 1$. We see also that for extreme values of emotional valencies $v=1$, $v=6$ and $v=7$, the exponent $\alpha$ reaches its lowest values (Fig.~\ref{fig:tfs-iaps-zyg-val}) that seem different than those for other scores. Additionally in Fig.~\ref{fig:tfs-iaps-zyg-aro} highly aroused states ($a=7$) can be identified. In COR, most scores show $\alpha\approx1$ but seem to drop to $\alpha\approx 0.85$ for very positive ($v=7$, Fig~\ref{fig:tfs-iaps-cor-val}) and very aroused states ($a=6$, $a=7$, Fig~\ref{fig:tfs-iaps-cor-aro}). PHSC results (Figs.~\ref{fig:tfs-iaps-phsc-val} and~\ref{fig:tfs-iaps-phsc-aro}) are very noisy and no clear trends are visible but $0.5<\alpha<1$ in all cases. The signal assumption of non-negativity of the signal is not fulfilled -- some results had negative means and thus they were filtered out.

